    "response_text": "Vaccines work by training the immune system to recognize and fight off specific pathogens, such as viruses or bacteria, without causing the disease itself. Here’s a breakdown of the process:\n\n1. **Introduction of Antigen**: Vaccines contain antigens, which are usually weakened or inactivated forms of the pathogen or pieces of it (like proteins or sugars). These antigens are recognized by the immune system as foreign substances.\n\n2. **Immune System Response**: When the vaccine is introduced into the body, the immune system recognizes these antigens as threats and mounts a response. This involves the activation of various components of the immune system, including B cells and T cells.\n\n3. **Production of Antibodies**: B cells produce antibodies that specifically target the antigens present in the vaccine. These antibodies can neutralize the pathogen if it enters the body in the future.\n\n4. **Memory Cells Formation**: In addition to producing antibodies, some B cells and T cells become memory cells. These",
